by Valentine Z » Fri Dec 25, 2020 12:36 am

Before reading anything, I want to preface a funny thought - I thought you are Rapture Republic because of his recent puppet with the similar color scheme. So... there's that!

-----

A couple of things:

While the Commonwealth was glad of the existence of the Confederation at first, cooperation and diplomatic friendship did not last long between the two polities as ideological differences between the xenophile and egalitarian Confederation and the authoritarian organisation of the Commonwealth that, while not xenophobic, did not view the relationships held between Humans and other species of the Confederation well.

Interspecies prejudice can be difficult to get rid of, I can relate. I mean, sure, I can be as inclusive as you can get, but even I would be a little wary to be standing besides the Covenant. Also, I think the sentence is a bit of a run-on, or is missing some words. I did not mean to play teacher, but I could not read it without getting lost in the middle. I might rewrite it like this, just as a suggestion! ♥

While the Commonwealth was glad of the existence of the Confederation at first, cooperation and diplomatic friendship did not last long between the two polities due to the ideological differences between the xenophile and egalitarian Confederation, against the authoritarian organisation of the Commonwealth which, while not xenophobic, did not view the relationships held between Humans and other species of the Confederation well.

-----

To properly overhaul the military, the Commonwealth lifted compulsory military service and replaced the all-draft military to a fully professional, volunteer and paid defense force.

That sounds pretty nice, but I can only hope that they have the funds and means to pay them. Not all the mercenaries are gold-diggers are movies and TV shows make them out to be; some of them stayed with the country they were hired or are fighting for. Hopefully this paid defense force will have people like Bartolomeo Colleoni who does not force a paycheck on you and fights till his death.

* Bartolomeo Colleoni was an Italian condottiero, who became captain-general of the Republic of Venice. I think I have also heard of another Portuguese (or maybe he was an Italian all along) back in my Social Studies class who was a mercenary but stayed with Venice. It was something about how overreliance on mercs can be dangerous, but hey, if this works for Commonwealth, why not!

-----

For BN, just a word of warning that you might not want to use the Overview / Wiki factbook's numbers for history; I have yet to update the years and all the smaller bits. ^^;

In March of 1988 the four ships constructed as part of the Exodus Initiative arrived at their destination, a spatial anomaly located within the Oort Cloud. This anomaly revealed itself to be a natural wormhole, albeit one unstable. This instability would lead to the disappearance of three out of the four ships as all were propelled through it while the wormhole collapsed. Two of the vessels' whereabouts remain unknown to this day. One ship, The Mayflower was discovered to have been ejected nearly two centuries in the future in the general vicinity of the Vrek system with evidence to suggest that the crew turned on itself, killing and cannibalizing eachother. The Speedwell was the only ship to survive with the ship emerging in the year 2020 and being within reasonable distance of a habitable stellar body.

Ah, well firstly the membership services aren't exactly direct Synnia-Foreign party agreements. Haukner & Kahn (now Haukner & Co.) is technically independent from the Synnian federal government though still maintains close-ish ties with the Synne Industries corporation, the tandem governing system makes this a bit of a mess but it's more or less its own thing. As for the memberships, they're mostly there to cater to governments and the especially affluent. Comparing this to real life, the United States Navy has an annual budget of roughly 161 billion USD and fields 11 fleet carriers. Haukner & Co.'s KING membership provides 8 carriers, very many guided missile cruisers and destroyers, and half an air force to boot, coming in at a total of roughly 190 billion USD and with far more advanced technologies mind you. Sverse maritime republics, the Panamanian League and Galapagos for example will be the primary customers for these large bundles while smaller quasi-nations such as the Silra group and various Rockwell city states are also there to get a piece of the smaller bundles. It's more or less a substitute for a proper defense force in terms of structure and equipment, purchasing parties need only supply the manpower, though training is still required.

As to the millionaire situation, it usually doesn't matter when it comes to the memberships due to the aforementioned examples of desired customers. That being said, Synnia's place in the world with the unnaturally high amount of business leaders and 'Human Singularity' situation probably means you'll know at least one person in your neighborhood whose got their hands on a Haukner & Co. guided missile cruiser.

For the naming and what it means, as with many things I chose it just because I thought it sounded cool at the moment, though you've done a pretty good job at interpretation. BISHOP membership is the first tier to have the rapid deployment and air-superiority bundles after all. I don't plan on adding any real limits as of now because, well, it's gonna be a while until I set up the proper storefront. But who knows? We've got until the heat death of the universe before I'll be able to finish all my factbook reduxes :}.

by Gemeanwealth of Man » Fri Dec 25, 2020 10:34 pm

The Armed Forces of Bloodshade is divided into three branches. The Army which is tasked with running planetside operations, the Navy which is tasked with running space operations, and the Special Arcane Forces. As with most interstellar militaries, the line between the former two branches is extremely muddy, with the navy being tasked with both transporting the army in cases of interplanetary expedition and -presumably- aid them in planetary incursion initiatives through orbital bombardment and information gathering through a bird eye view. The most impressive thing about it however, is neither the gargantuan size of the military nor the high number of ships currently in use. In case of total war, Bloodshade can draft up to 57% of its total population... which kinda scares me.

So, a few things I have learned: the fact that he is currently serving as the Grand Marshal in a 36-year war. That was impressive in both a commendable way, and as a sad way. Commendable because the man has dedication to raise the standards and quality of life around him. Sad because the poor man has been on it for 36 years and I am sure it is not his choice either. Imagine having to go through logistics and strategy constantly for 36 years. That is going to wear on someone very quickly. Hell, you can see it in his face! Also, very tall dude, I like.

Also this: Arnold joined the Commonwealth Military at the age of 20, originally in pursuit of a better quality of life that only military service can bring to the citizens of the Commonwealth. It must be the gourmet MREs that he was attracted by, hehe. Jokes aside and no lie, as someone who was drafted OOCly as part of Singapore's conscription thing, if there are no wars, your life in the military is pretty decent. You get free food, some free stuff (you need to buy with credits, but it's not technically with your money), accommodation, and the like, in exchange for freedom and regimentation! I imagine that life as a soldier in the Commonwealth Military will be better thanks to the much more advanced tech, though the trade-off being that the poor man has to fight an actual war, not just self-defense like me. So, as he has been around for so long, he definitely knows surviving!

Their first war against the 'Drule' race was actually against the pacifistic and isolationist 'Fifth' Kingdom, which had split off from the Third Kingdom, one which is oddly antagonistic to the Fifth Kingdom's beliefs. It was kind of lucky mankind encountered the Third Kingdom first because the Fifth Kingdom was actually the more powerful of the two states, meaning a war against them would have likely ended in a human defeat. The defeat of the Fifth Kingdom indirectly led to a technological renaissance within the CoM, which allowed the Third Kingdom to be swiftly defeated, in contrast to the long and drawn-out conflict that was the first-encounter war.
